<Base
  title="Methodology"
  description="Where every number comes from, the vetting ladder, the FCC no carrier name limit, and how social mentions are counted."
>
  <div class="wrap prose" data-pagefind-body>
    <h1>Methodology</h1>
    <p>
      This page explains where every number on the site comes from and how it is
      counted. A link to this page sits near every number.
    </p>

    <h2>Where the numbers come from</h2>
    <p>
      Public counts are built from records in the evidence tier. That tier
      includes arbitration files that name the company, court filings, federal
      enforcement actions, SEC filings, the FCC complaint dataset, and vetted
      stories people send us. Each record links to its public source. We publish
      pre aggregated counts, so the public files carry counts and locations
      only, never a story body or any personal identifier.
    </p>

    <h2>The vetting ladder</h2>
    <p>
      Every record sits on one of three rungs.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Single source.</strong> One source says it and nothing else
        corroborates it yet. This is a lead. It does not feed the public count.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Corroborated.</strong> More than one independent source supports
        it, or a primary document backs a secondary report.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Verified primary.</strong> A primary public document establishes
        it directly, for example an agency action or a filed court document.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Only the top two rungs, corroborated and verified primary, feed the public
      counts. The running verified count in the header is the strict count:
      corroborated plus verified primary only.
    </p>

    <h2>The FCC complaint limit, in plain words</h2>
    <p>
      The FCC informal complaint dataset gives us complaint volume by city,
      state, and ZIP. It does not include the name of the company complained
      about. There is no carrier name field in that data.
    </p>
    <p>
      So the map color layer built from it shows wireless billing complaint
      concentration for all carriers. We never present it as per carrier counts,
      because the data cannot support that. Per carrier numbers come only from
      sources where the company is named on the record, like arbitration files,
      court filings, and vetted stories.
    </p>

    <h2>Counting social mentions</h2>
    <p>
      From public platforms that allow it, we publish aggregate mention counts
      per carrier per month. We publish the count and the method, never an
      individual post. A single social post is a lead until it is vetted, not a
      public data point.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Deletion is honored.</strong> When a post is deleted at the
      source, it stops counting. Our counts reflect what still exists. We
      consume real delete events and drop removed posts, so an aggregate count
      never props up something the author took down.
    </p>

    <h2>What the public files contain</h2>
    <p>
      The site reads three published files. A map file with counts by state and
      by ZIP. A mentions file with monthly carrier mention counts by source. A
      totals file with the record total, the strict verified count, and the
      breakdown by vetting rung. These files carry numbers and locations only.
    </p>

    <h2>The line between fact and commentary</h2>
    <p>
      Documented practice is stated as fact, with a source. Any characterization
      of what the facts add up to is labeled as commentary. We never assert that
      carriers coordinate. We aim at practices and companies, never at
      individual employees. Real numbers only. We never inflate.
    </p>

    <h2>Corrections</h2>
    <p>
      When we get a number or a claim wrong, we fix it in the open. See the
      <a href="/corrections">corrections page</a> and the
      <a href="/legal/corrections-policy">corrections policy</a>.
    </p>
  </div>
</Base>
